10.body: The Java standard library is a useful tool, and you should learn how to use it. However, these projects are meant to be completed with the limited tools we cover in class, and the standard library can trivialize some problems that you're meant to solve by hand. You're free to make use of any String methods, any of the IO and Math functions we've covered, and parsing functions (like Integer.parseInt). However, using other parts of the standard library that we haven't covered, such as System or Scanner, is not allowed. You're also not allowed to use any third-party libraries in autograded assignments.

13.body: Dungeons and Dragons is a tabletop roleplaying game (TTRPG). Even if you haven't played a TTRPG before, you've probably still heard the name "Dungeons and Dragons" at some point. These assignments will use a modified version of some character creation rules from D&D 5e. The real rules can be found in the 5e System Reference Document (SRD), which you can read if you're curious and want to learn more. However, you do not need to read the SRD for this assignment.
13.breadcrumbs: Character Sheet Project » Dungeons and Dragons
13.title: Dungeons and Dragons

14.body: The idea behind these assignments is to write a program that generates a "character sheet" for someone playing a TTRPG like D&D. A player normally controls a fictional character (their Player Character, or PC), and they track information about their character on a character sheet. This might include statistics, like how strong or fast the character is, the character's possessions, or information about the character's personality. The character sheet you generate will not cover all of the information about a real TTRPG character. This would get too complicated for an early programming assignment. Instead, we'll use a small subset of rules from the SRD, some of which will be simplified to better fit this assignment. You don't need to know any of these rules! The assignments will explain any calculations your code needs to perform.
14.title: Character Sheet

15.body: Below is a summary of some terms that will come up in this assignment: A character's class is the role they fill in the game's world. In a game like D&D, which focuses on fighting fantasy monsters, a character's class tells us their role in combat. A wizard casts spells, a rogue sneaks up on enemies, and a fighter... fights. Yes, everyone fights, but the fighter fights more directly, like with a sword and shield. A character's ancestry or race (the term varies by game, but I'll usually default to ancestry) represents what kind of creature they are. D&D includes a lot of your standard fantasy races: elf, human, dwarf, goblin, gnome, halfling, and orc. However, depending on the game and who's running it, a TTRPG character could be anything: a ghost, a dragon, a talking bear, or a mannequin. I have run a game of D&D that included both a talking bear and a mannequin as player characters. The mannequin also talked, and his name was Bob. The bear had a pet monkey. All of this will be on the exam [1] . A character's hit points (HP) represent how difficult they are to defeat in combat. A character's armor class (AC) represents how hard they are to hit with an attack. A high AC may mean that a character is very good at avoiding attacks, or that a character is wearing armor that blocks most attacks. A character's ability scores are numbers that represent a character's strength, cunning, speed, and other innate qualities. These affect most actions in the game. A character's ability modifiers are bonuses or penalties derived from their ability scores. The modifiers are the numbers we actually use in most calculations, and the scores only exist to determine the modifiers. At this point, you may be wondering why we bother with ability scores if we don't use them after calculating the modifiers. Good question! Anyway, let's talk about the character's level. A character's level represents how powerful and experienced they are. In most TTRPGs, characters gain experience and level up to represent how they've grown during their adventures. In addition to standard six-sided dice (referred to as D6 dice), D&D uses several less common dice shapes: D4, D8, D10, D12, and D20. We don't have exams, don't worry.
15.title: Terminology

18.body: Write this program in a file named CharacterSheet1.java. Prompt the user for the following information (in order): The player's name (String) The character's name (String) The character's class (String) The character's ancestry (String) The character's level (int) The character's strength score (int) The character's dexterity score (int) The character's constitution score (int) Print each of these values back in the same order (player name, character name, etc.). Each value should be printed on a separate line. Print only the value, no label! Print the sum of the level, strength score, dexterity score, and constitution score. One problem you might run into with this program is that "class" is a Java keyword. It would be natural to use class as the name for the variable that holds the character's class, but Java won't allow keywords as identifiers. The name "clazz" is sometimes used as a workaround, but any other name that still conveys the purpose of the variable is fine.

4.body: Tests will normally check the following: Output produced by IO.println and IO.print. Your program's output must match any requirements given in the assignment. Any difference (wrong spelling, capitalization, spacing, etc.) will fail an I/O test. All programs should end their output with a newline character, which usually means using IO.println for your last print statement, and avoid trailing whitespace in their output. Values returned by your function. If your function returns a value, then the value must match any requirements given in the assignment. Modifications to array arguments passed to your function. If your function takes any array parameters, then it must modify them as described in the assignment's requirements. Any extra modifications will cause a test to fail. Tests will always ignore any output produced by IO.readln. I never specify how exactly to prompt the user for input, so you may word these prompts however you want. The tests will only look at output from IO.print and IO.println. This also means you shouldn't use IO.readln to print any of the required output. A few other ways for a test to fail: Prompting for additional input or prompting in the wrong order. The test provides input in the order described in the assignment, so your code needs to read it in the same order. Printing output in the wrong order, combining separate lines into the same line, or splitting up one line into several lines.
4.title: Test Criteria

40.body: Yahtzee is a game played with five dice per player over 13 rounds. Each player's goal is to earn the most points by the end of the game. A round of Yahtzee consists of the following steps: Each player rolls all of their dice. Each player chooses any number of their dice to reroll and rerolls all of the chosen dice at the same time. They can then repeat this process one more time. Each player chooses one of thirteen categories on their scorecard. Each category can only be chosen once per player and is worth points based on the dice rolled. For example, choosing the yahtzee category is worth 50 points if all of your dice show the same number and 0 points otherwise. At the end of the game, each player adds up their points. The player with the most points wins.
40.title: Yahtzee

50.body: Write this program in a file named DiceGame2.java and start with a copy of your code from the previous assignment. Remove the "Dice Game" print statement from your main function and divide it into three sections (you can mark the sections with comments): initialization, rerolling, and scoring. Initialization: Create an int array for your dice and randomize its elements with your rollAllDice function. Create a variable to track your remaining rerolls and initialize it to 2. Rerolling: create a loop that repeats while the user has at least one reroll left. Inside the loop: Print the dice using printDice and prompt the user for a command. If the user enters "skip", then set their rerolls to 0. This should end the loop. If the user enters "roll", then Ask them which dice to reroll. Assume their answer consists only of letters from 'a' to 'e' and use your parseReroll and rollSomeDice functions to reroll the appropriate dice. Decrease their rerolls by 1. If the user enters anything else, then print an error message. Scoring: Print the user's dice so they can see the result of their last reroll. Prompt the user for a die value to score (an integer from 1 to 6). If the user enters a number outside this range, then print an error message and repeat the prompt until you get a valid number. Calculate the user's score with calculateScore and print it.

58.body: The game allows the user to choose from ten different score categories: Aces Twos Threes Fours Fives Sixes 3 of a Kind 4 of a Kind Yahtzee Chance The rules for calculating these scores are as follows: The first six categories (the "upper categories" in Yahtzee) are scored the same as in previous assignments: the category number multiplied by how many dice equal that number. The 3 and 4 of a kind categories follow similar rules: If the user has at least three (3 of a kind) or at least four (4 of a kind) dice with the same number, then these categories are worth the sum of all dice (not just the matching dice). If the user doesn't meet the 3/4 of a kind requirement, then these categories are worth 0 points. The Yahtzee category is worth 50 points if all of the dice are the same and 0 points otherwise. The chance category is always worth the sum of all dice.
58.breadcrumbs: Dice Game Project » Assignment 7 » Score Categories
58.title: Score Categories

62.title: Autograded

63.body: Write this program in a file named DiceGame4.java and start with a copy of your code from the previous assignment. Modify your printScores function to take two parameters: an array of ten scores and an array of five dice. The array of scores represents scores from previous rounds, with a negative value indicating a category that hasn't been selected. When you print each category: if the score in the array isn't negative, show that number instead of calculating a score with the dice if the score in the array is negative, show "available (X)", where X is the score calculated for the given dice, to indicate that the user can choose this category and would receive the amount of points shown Modify your playRound function to take a parameter for the scores array. You'll need to pass this array when you print the scores. Make the following changes to the scoring part of the function: Change your input validation to ensure the user chooses a category from 1 to 10 with a negative score. Remember to subtract 1 from the category number before using it to index the scores array (categories are 1-10, but score indexes are 0-9). Change the error message to ERROR: You cannot score category X., where X is the user's invalid input. The old message doesn't make sense now that we're choosing from ten categories instead of six die values. Store the user's score in the scores array at the appropriate index. Modify your main function to do the following: Create an array of ten scores and initialize each element to -1. Call your playRound function ten times (use a loop), passing it the scores array as an argument. It will add one score to the array with each round, replacing the negative number. Find the total score after ten rounds and print Game Over! Your total score is: X., replacing X with the total score. Print the score categories one more time. You'll need to pass it an array for the dice, even though it won't use the array, so just make a new temporary array and pass that as the second argument.
